column2: Does your child ever talk about past events or people who are not present? For example
column3: a child who saw a parade last week might later say parade

column2: Does your child ever talk about something that's going to happen in the future
column4: saying ‘choo choo’ or ‘aeroplane’ before you leave the house for a trip
column5: or saying ‘swing’ when you are going to the park?

column2: Does your child talk about objects that are not present such as asking about a missing or absent toy
column3: referring to a pet out of view
column4: or asking about someone not present?

column2: Does your child understand if you ask for something that is not in the room? For example
column3: would your child go to the bedroom to get a teddy bear when you say ‘Where's the bear?’

column2: Does your child ever pick up or point to an object and name an absent person to whom the object belongs? For example
column3: a child might point to mummy's shoe and say ‘mummy’.

column2: To talk about more than one thing
column3: we add an ‘s’ to many words. Examples include carS (for more than one car)
column6: and keyS. Has your child begun to do this?

column7: and baby'S bottle. Has your child begun to do this?

column3: we sometimes add ‘ing’ to verbs. Examples include lookING
column4: suckING and cryING. Has your child begun to do this?

column2: To talk about things that happened in the past
column3: we often add ‘ed’ to the verb. Examples include kissED
column4: openED and pushED. Has your child begun to do this?
